VAPT Assignment – Theoretical & Practical Work
 Overview

This repository contains my work for the Vulnerability Assessment and Penetration Testing (VAPT) assignment.
The objective of this task is to understand the basics of security assessment, perform vulnerability scanning using open-source tools, and document the findings in a structured way.

The assignment is divided into two parts:

Theoretical Knowledge
Practical Implementation
 Theoretical Knowledge
1. Understanding Security Assessment

Security assessment is the process of identifying weaknesses in a system. It helps in understanding how secure a system is and what needs improvement.

Different types of testing covered:

Vulnerability Assessment – Finding known weaknesses using tools like OpenVAS
Penetration Testing – Simulating real-world attacks using tools such as Nmap and Metasploit
Compliance Testing – Checking whether systems follow standards like CIS benchmarks
2. VAPT Methodology

A structured approach was followed to perform testing:

Planning – Defining scope and target systems
Discovery – Scanning using tools like Nmap and OWASP ZAP
Attack – Exploiting vulnerabilities (where applicable)
Reporting – Documenting findings clearly
3. Security Standards & Compliance

Basic understanding of industry standards such as:

GDPR
HIPAA
ISO 27001

Also studied OWASP Top 10 to understand common web vulnerabilities.

4. Risk Assessment Basics

Learned how to prioritize vulnerabilities based on risk:

Used CVSS scoring system
Categorized risks into High, Medium, and Low
Created a simple risk matrix
5. Common Vulnerabilities

Studied and practiced identifying:

Network issues – Open ports, misconfigurations
Web vulnerabilities – SQL Injection, XSS

Used practice environments like vulnerable machines to understand real scenarios.

6. Documentation Fundamentals

Maintained proper documentation of findings using:

Notes for observations
Screenshots as proof
Structured reporting format
🛠️ Practical Implementation
1. Environment Setup
Installed Kali Linux
Set up Metasploitable virtual machine
Configured VirtualBox for testing
2. Vulnerability Scanning

Tools used:

OpenVAS
Nikto

Performed scans on the target machine and collected:

Open ports
Running services
Detected vulnerabilities
3. Documentation of Findings

Recorded the following details:

Target IP address
Open ports and services
Description of vulnerabilities
Supporting screenshots
4. Risk Assessment
Used CVSS scoring for each vulnerability
Classified risks based on severity
Prioritized issues for fixing
5. Report Creation

Prepared a detailed report including:

Executive Summary
Technical Findings
Risk Analysis
Remediation Suggestions

